===== bsearch =====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
void* bsearch( const void *key, const void *base, size_t num, size_t size, int (*compare)(const void *, const void *));
</source>
}}

The function bsearch() performs a search within a sorted array, returning a pointer to the element in question or '''NULL'''. 

''*key'' refers to an object that matches an item searched within ''*base''.  This array contains ''num'' elements, each of size ''size''.  

The ''compare'' function accepts two pointers to the object within the array - which need to first be cast to the object type being examined.  The function returns -1 if the first parameter should be before the second, 1 if the first parameter is after, or 0 if the object matches.  

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/qsort|qsort]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== qsort ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
void* qsort( const void *base, size_t num, size_t size, int (*compare)(const void *, const void *));
</source>
}}

The function qsort() performs a [[w:quicksort|Quick sort]] on an array.  Note that some implementations may instead use a more efficient sorting algorithm. 

''*base'' refers to the array being sorted.  This array contains ''num'' elements, each of size ''size''.  

The ''compare'' function accepts two pointers to the object within the array - which need to first be cast to the object type being examined.  The function returns -1 if the first parameter should be before the second, 1 if the first parameter is after, or 0 if the object matches.  

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/bsearch|bsearch]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== free ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
void free( void *p);
</source>
}}

The function free() releases a previously allocated block from a call to calloc, malloc, or realloc.  

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/calloc|calloc]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/malloc|malloc]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/realloc|realloc]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== Standard C Memory Management ====

This section will cover memory management elements from the Standard C Library.

{{NOTE|It is recommended to use the new and delete operators instead of these functions, as they provide additional control over the creation of objects.}}

{{:C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/calloc}}
{{:C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/free}}
{{:C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/malloc}}
{{:C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/realloc}}

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== calloc ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
void *calloc( size_t num, size_t size);
</source>
}}

The function calloc() allocates a block of memory that can store ''num'' objects of size ''size''.  In addition, the block of memory allocated is set to all zeros.  

If the operation fails, calloc() returns '''NULL'''. 

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/free|free]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/malloc|malloc]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/realloc|realloc]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== malloc ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
void *malloc( size_t s );
</source>
}}

The function malloc() allocates a block of memory of size ''s''.  The memory remains uninitialized.

If the operation fails, malloc() returns '''NULL'''. 

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/calloc|calloc]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/free|free]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/realloc|realloc]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== realloc ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
void *realloc( void *p, size_t s);
</source>
}}

The function realloc() resizes a block created by malloc() or calloc(), and returns a pointer to the new memory region.

If the resize operation fails, realloc() returns '''NULL''' and leaves the old memory region intact.  

{{NOTE|realloc() does not have a corresponding operator in C++ - however, this is not required since the standard template library already provides the necessary memory management for most usages.}}

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/calloc|calloc]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/free|free]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/malloc|malloc]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

