==== vscanf, vfscanf, and vsscanf ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdarg>
#include <cstdio>
int vscanf( const char *format, va_list arg_ptr );
int vfscanf( FILE *stream, const char *format, va_list arg_ptr );
int vsscanf( const char *buffer, const char *format, va_list arg_ptr );
</source>
}}

{{NOTE|These functions are not supported on all libraries.}}

These functions are very much like [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/scanf|scanf]](), [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/fscanf|fscanf]](), and [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sscanf|sscanf]](). The difference is that the argument list is a pointer to a list of arguments. '''va_list''' is defined in cstdarg, and is also used by (Other Standard C Functions) [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/va_arg|va_arg]](). 

For example:

<source lang=cpp>
void error( char *fmt, ... ) {
  va_list args;
  va_start( args, fmt );
  fprintf( stderr, "Error: " );
  vfprintf( stderr, fmt, args );
  fprintf( stderr, "\n" );
  va_end( args );
  exit( 1 );
}   
</source>

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

